  <description type="morphology">Plants 15–30 cm; setae whitish, conspicuously curled or crisped (1–2 mm). Stems densely setose or tomentose. Leaves: petioles setose; blades 10–15 × 3–4 cm (tomentulose or glabrate, midribs setose). Involucres 12–17 mm. Phyllaries densely setose or tomentose. Cypselae greenish black, 7–10 mm, beaked (beaks 1–2 mm, ribs alternating strong and weak); pappi 7–10 mm. 2n = 22, 33, 44.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering May–Jul.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Dry open places, rocky ridges;</description>
  <description type="elevation">1000–1100 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">B.C.; Wash.</description>
  <number>11c.</number>
  <discussion>Subspecies rostrata is distinguished mainly by the dense curly setae of the involucres and cypselae with relatively short, coarse beaks.</discussion>
